Hi guys,

I posted the following rabbit promo post on a Reddit forum a while ago and thought why not post it here. Maybe it will be useful info for someone.

I live on a to-be self sufficient farmstead in Lapland Sweden and by far our most profitable animal on the farm when it comes to meat is rabbits. 🐰

They yield about 6 times more meat per unit of feed, than a cow. And before you disregard rabbit meat, it actually tastes amazing, is high in protein ratio and very similar to chicken!

They're easy to keep, and breed like crazy. One female can produce 6-10 babies at once, that are ready to be slaughtered 4-6 months later at ~2 kg of meat each. And that's just one female, and one cull. At the moment we keep about 10 females to be bred next spring.

Also they can eat hay/grass only, so you can have them turning the grass in your back garden into delicious, high protein meat! If you haven't got enough grass on your land, you can scythe wherever you can, on public land, and bring it to your rabbits, or buy pellets/hay of course.

Apparently rabbits were very common in Europe during the second world war because of the meat yield, but now most people have forgotten. In some European countries (like France) it's still possible to buy rabbit in the supermarkets.

The best resource I've found in on YouTube, therabbitrycenter I think they're called, lots of great tips there.
